aa(lp59
VAnd so, the question for my lab is whether you want to think about all the
p60
aVgood things that bacteria do, or all the bad things that bacteria do.
p61
aVThe question we had is how could they do anything at all?
p62
aVI mean they're incredibly small,
p63
aVyou have to have a microscope to see one.
p64
aVThey live this sort of boring life where they grow and divide,
p65
aVand they've always been considered to be these asocial reclusive organisms.
p66
aVAnd so it seemed to us that they are just too small to have an impact
p67
aVon the environment
p68
aVif they simply act as individuals.
p69
aVAnd so we wanted to think if there couldn't be a different
p70
aVway that bacteria live.
p71
aa(lp72
VThe clue to this came from another marine bacterium,
p73
aVand it's a bacterium called Vibrio fischeri.
p74
aVWhat you're looking at on this slide is just a person from my lab
p75
aVholding a flask of a liquid culture of a bacterium,
p76
aVa harmless beautiful bacterium that comes from the ocean,
p77
aVnamed Vibrio fischeri.
p78
aVThis bacterium has the special property that it makes light,
p79
aVso it makes bioluminescence,
p80
aVlike fireflies make light.
p81
aVWe're not doing anything to the cells here.
p82
aVWe just took the picture by turning the lights off in the room,
p83
aVand this is what we see.
p84
aa(lp85
VWhat was actually interesting to us
p86
aVwas not that the bacteria made light,
p87
aVbut when the bacteria made light.
p88
aVWhat we noticed is when the bacteria were alone,
p89
aVso when they were in dilute suspension, they made no light.
p90
aVBut when they grew to a certain cell number
p91
aVall the bacteria turned on light simultaneously.
p92
aVThe question that we had is how can bacteria, these primitive organisms,
p93
aVtell the difference from times when they're alone,
p94
aVand times when they're in a community,
p95
aVand then all do something together.
p96
aVWhat we've figured out is that the way that they do that is that they talk to each other,
p97
aVand they talk with a chemical language.
p98
aa(lp99
VThis is now supposed to be my bacterial cell.
p100
aVWhen it's alone it doesn't make any light.
p101
aVBut what it does do is to make and secrete small molecules
p102
aVthat you can think of like hormones,
p103
aVand these are the red triangles, and when the bacteria is alone
p104
aVthe molecules just float away and so no light.
p105
aVBut when the bacteria grow and double
p106
aVand they're all participating in making these molecules,
p107
aVthe molecule \u2014 the extracellular amount of that molecule
p108
aVincreases in proportion to cell number.
p109
aVAnd when the molecule hits a certain amount
p110
aVthat tells the bacteria how many neighbors there are,
p111
aVthey recognize that molecule
p112
aVand all of the bacteria turn on light in synchrony.
p113
aVThat's how bioluminescence works \u2014
p114
aVthey're talking with these chemical words.
p115
aa(lp116
VThe reason that Vibrio fischeri is doing that comes from the biology.
p117
aVAgain, another plug for the animals in the ocean,
p118
aVVibrio fischeri lives in this squid.
p119
aVWhat you are looking at is the Hawaiian Bobtail Squid,
p120
aVand it's been turned on its back,
p121
aVand what I hope you can see are these two glowing lobes
p122
aVand these house the Vibrio fischeri cells,
p123
aVthey live in there, at high cell number
p124
aVthat molecule is there, and they're making light.
p125
aVThe reason the squid is willing to put up with these shenanigans
p126
aVis because it wants that light.
p127
aVThe way that this symbiosis works
p128
aVis that this little squid lives just off the coast of Hawaii,
p129
aVjust in sort of shallow knee-deep water.
p130
aVThe squid is nocturnal, so during the day
p131
aVit buries itself in the sand and sleeps,
p132
aVbut then at night it has to come out to hunt.
p133
aVOn bright nights when there is lots of starlight or moonlight
p134
aVthat light can penetrate the depth of the water
p135
aVthe squid lives in, since it's just in those couple feet of water.
p136
aVWhat the squid has developed is a shutter
p137
aVthat can open and close over this specialized light organ housing the bacteria.
p138
aVThen it has detectors on its back
p139
aVso it can sense how much starlight or moonlight is hitting its back.
p140
aVAnd it opens and closes the shutter
p141
aVso the amount of light coming out of the bottom \u2014
p142
aVwhich is made by the bacterium \u2014
p143
aVexactly matches how much light hits the squid's back,
p144
aVso the squid doesn't make a shadow.
p145
aVIt actually uses the light from the bacteria
p146
aVto counter-illuminate itself in an anti-predation device
p147
aVso predators can't see its shadow,
p148
aVcalculate its trajectory, and eat it.
p149
aVThis is like the stealth bomber of the ocean.
p150
aa(lp151
V(Laughter)
p152
aa(lp153
VBut then if you think about it, the squid has this terrible problem
p154
aVbecause it's got this dying, thick culture of bacteria
p155
aVand it can't sustain that.
p156
aVAnd so what happens is every morning when the sun comes up
p157
aVthe squid goes back to sleep, it buries itself in the sand,
p158
