aa(lp186
VWhy this is interesting is because in the past decade
p187
aVwe have found that this is not just some anomaly
p188
aVof this ridiculous, glow-in-the-dark bacterium that lives in the ocean \u2014
p189
aVall bacteria have systems like this.
p190
aVSo now what we understand is that all bacteria can talk to each other.
p191
aVThey make chemical words, they recognize those words,
p192
aVand they turn on group behaviors
p193
aVthat are only successful when all of the cells participate in unison.
p194
aVWe have a fancy name for this: we call it quorum sensing.
p195
aVThey vote with these chemical votes,
p196
aVthe vote gets counted, and then everybody responds to the vote.
p197
aa(lp198
VWhat's important for today's talk
p199
aVis that we know that there are hundreds of behaviors
p200
aVthat bacteria carry out in these collective fashions.
p201
aVBut the one that's probably the most important to you is virulence.
p202
aVIt's not like a couple bacteria get in you
p203
aVand they start secreting some toxins \u2014
p204
aVyou're enormous, that would have no effect on you. You're huge.
p205
aVWhat they do, we now understand,
p206
aVis they get in you, they wait, they start growing,
p207
aVthey count themselves with these little molecules,
p208
aVand they recognize when they have the right cell number
p209
aVthat if all of the bacteria launch their virulence attack together,
p210
aVthey are going to be successful at overcoming an enormous host.
p211
aVBacteria always control pathogenicity with quorum sensing.
p212
aVThat's how it works.
